06705nam a22008895i 9783111292069DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831112920697 a10.1515/97831112920692doi  a(DE-B1597)652500  a(OCoLC)1399980498  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh0485pa090qDE-10100aTied and Bound: A Comparative View on Manuscript Binding /ced. by Alessandro Bausi, Michael Friedrich. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VI, 389 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Manuscript Cultures ,x2365-9696 ;v3300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTied and Bound: A Tight Preface -- tOverviews of Traditions -- tBinding Cuneiform Tablets in One Unit -- tBindings of Ancient Chinese Bamboo and Wood Scrolls -- tChains, Links, and Loops: Towards a Deeper Understanding of the Sewing Structure in Eastern Mediterranean Bookbinding -- tBindings, Bags and Boxes: Sewn and Unsewn Manuscript Formats in the Islamic World -- tStrategies for Binding Pothi Manuscripts -- tGuṭakās from North-Western India: An Introduction to their Structures and Materials -- tFeatures of Binding -- tPapyrus Rolls as Archives: The tomoi sunkollēsimoi -- tEthiopian and Coptic Sewing Techniques in Comparison -- tLoose-leaf Islamic Manuscripts of West Africa: Retention, Adaptation or Invention? -- tLegacy of Binding -- tBound to be Rebound: Fates of Latin Manuscripts in Late Antiquity -- tBound and Unbound: A Chinese Codex from Dunhuang and Its Pieces -- tBinding or Rebinding at St Catherine's Monastery of Sinai -- tContributors -- tIndexes -- tGeneral Index0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe present volume contains twelve chapters authored by specialists of Asian, African and European manuscript cultures reflecting on the cohesion of written artefacts, particularly manuscripts. Assuming that 'codicological units' exist in every manuscript culture and that they are usually composed of discrete elements (such as clay tablets, papyrus sheets, bamboo slips, parchment bifolios, palm leaves), the issue of the cohesion of the constituents is a general one. The volume presents a series of case studies on devices and strategies adopted to achieve this cohesion by manuscript cultures distant in space (from China to West Africa) and time (from the third millennium bce to the present). This comparative view provides the frame for the understanding of a phenomenon that appears to be of essential importance for the study of the structure of written artefacts. Regardless of the way in which cohesion is realised, all strategies and devices that allow the constituents to be kept together are subsumed under the term 'binding'. Thus, it is possible to highlight similarities, convergences, and unique physical and technical methods adopted by various manuscript cultures to face a common challenge.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aArchiv. 4aBuchwissenschaft. 4aHandschriftenkunde. 4aKonservierung. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aBook history.  aarchive.  acodicology.  apreservation.1 aAmmirati, Serena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBausi, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBausi, Alessandro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBondarev, Dmitry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoudalis, Georgios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiotti, 